    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-10-21T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-10-21T05:00:00-05:00" n="1141"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1141">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/10–2149: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Strong</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-10-21T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >October 21, 1949—5 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 21—7:21 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Cantel 1217. Chen Tai-chu<note n="86" xml:id="d1141fn86">Foreign Office American
                        Department Chief.</note> today admitted Chinese Navy released <hi
                        rend="italic">Flying Trader</hi> as well as two other Isbrandtsen ships on
                    own responsibility and that Foreign Office does not yet have details. Chen
                    previously claimed Foreign Office dictated policy on detention and release
                    (Cantel 1202, October 12).</p>
                <p>Chen felt Navy probably had insufficient vessels for continued detention these
                    ships view combat commitments. He referred with gratification to message he
                    claimed received from Chinese Embassy to effect Department advised it not
                    encouraging US flag vessels violate closure.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Strong</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
